Regularized regression

Jeffrey Leek

Basic idea

  1. Fit a regression model
  2. Penalize (or shrink) large coefficients

Pros:

  • Can help with the bias/variance tradeoff
  • Can help with model selection

Cons:

  • May be computationally demanding on large data sets
  • Does not perform as well as random forests and boosting

A motivating example

Y=β0+β1X1+β2X2+ϵY=β0+β1X1+β2X2+ϵ

where X1X1 and X2X2 are nearly perfectly correlated (co-linear). You can approximate this model by:

Y=β0+(β1+β2)X1+ϵY=β0+(β1+β2)X1+ϵ

The result is:

  • You will get a good estimate of YY
  • The estimate (of YY) will be biased
  • We may reduce variance in the estimate

Model selection approach: split samples

  • No method better when data/computation time permits it

  • Approach
  1. Divide data into training/test/validation
  2. Treat validation as test data, train all competing models on the train data and pick the best one on validation.
  3. To appropriately assess performance on new data apply to test set
  4. You may re-split and reperform steps 1-3
  • Two common problems
  • Limited data
  • Computational complexity

http://www.biostat.jhsph.edu/~ririzarr/Teaching/649/ http://www.cbcb.umd.edu/~hcorrada/PracticalML/

Decomposing expected prediction error

Assume Yi=f(Xi)+ϵiYi=f(Xi)+ϵi

EPE(λ)=E[{Y−f^λ(X)}2]EPE(λ)=E[{Y−f^λ(X)}2]

Suppose f^λf^λ is the estimate from the training data and look at a new data point X=x∗X=x∗

E[{Y−f^λ(x∗)}2]=σ2+{E[f^λ(x∗)]−f(x∗)}2+var[f^λ(x0)]E[{Y−f^λ(x∗)}2]=σ2+{E[f^λ(x∗)]−f(x∗)}2+var[f^λ(x0)]

= Irreducible error + Bias22 + Variance

Hard thresholding

  • Model Y=f(X)+ϵY=f(X)+ϵ

  • Set f^λ(x)=x′βf^λ(x)=x′β

  • Constrain only λλ coefficients to be nonzero.

  • Selection problem is after chosing λλ figure out which p−λp−λ coefficients to make nonzero

http://www.biostat.jhsph.edu/~ririzarr/Teaching/649/ http://www.cbcb.umd.edu/~hcorrada/PracticalML/

Regularization for regression

If the βjβj’s are unconstrained: * They can explode * And hence are susceptible to very high variance

To control variance, we might regularize/shrink the coefficients.

PRSS(β)=∑j=1n(Yj−∑i=1mβ1iXij)2+P(λ;β)PRSS(β)=∑j=1n(Yj−∑i=1mβ1iXij)2+P(λ;β)

where PRSSPRSS is a penalized form of the sum of squares. Things that are commonly looked for

  • Penalty reduces complexity
  • Penalty reduces variance
  • Penalty respects structure of the problem

Ridge regression

Solve:

∑i=1N(yi−β0+∑j=1pxijβj)2+λ∑j=1pβ2j∑i=1N(yi−β0+∑j=1pxijβj)2+λ∑j=1pβj2

equivalent to solving

∑Ni=1(yi−β0+∑pj=1xijβj)2∑i=1N(yi−β0+∑j=1pxijβj)2 subject to ∑pj=1β2j≤s∑j=1pβj2≤s where ss is inversely proportional to λλ

Inclusion of λλ makes the problem non-singular even if XTXXTX is not invertible.

Tuning parameter λλ

  • λλ controls the size of the coefficients
  • λλ controls the amount of {}
  • As λ→0λ→0 we obtain the least square solution
  • As λ→∞λ→∞ we have β^ridgeλ=∞=0β^λ=∞ridge=0

Lasso

∑Ni=1(yi−β0+∑pj=1xijβj)2∑i=1N(yi−β0+∑j=1pxijβj)2 subject to ∑pj=1|βj|≤s∑j=1p|βj|≤s

also has a lagrangian form

∑i=1N(yi−β0+∑j=1pxijβj)2+λ∑j=1p|βj|∑i=1N(yi−β0+∑j=1pxijβj)2+λ∑j=1p|βj|

For orthonormal design matrices (not the norm!) this has a closed form solution

β^j=sign(β^0j)(|β^0j−γ)+β^j=sign(β^j0)(|β^j0−γ)+

but not in general.
